{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"528f0cb0-4395-4086-893c-671f602951ab","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically generates **`.ips` crash reports** when a process crashes. You don't need `createdump`.\n\n**Where to find them:**\n\n- **`~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — crash reports for your user\n- **`/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/`** — system-wide crash reports\n\nLook for a file named like `YourAppName_YYYY-MM-DD-HHMMSS_machinename.ips`.\n\n**Quick way to find it:**\n\n```bash\nls -lt ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/*.ips | head -5\n```\n\n**To read it:**\n\n```bash\ncat ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/YourAppName*.ips\n```\n\nThe `.ips` file contains the crash thread's backtrace, signal info (e.g., `EXC_BAD_ACCESS`, `SIGABRT`), and loaded library addresses. If you need to symbolicate the .NET runtime frames, you can use `atos` with debug symbols from the Microsoft symbol server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"25fc69f6-b47f-4273-8f0a-aa76896144a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search any codebase. Let me answer directly.","outputTokens":333,"requestId":"6808:2234D2:18EFB6D:1BF6D1F:69FD41A6"},"id":"a2b75abe-1452-4995-8f30-53bf40f66469","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:51:45.688Z","parentId":"6c689d56-baa9-4278-9f35-5ffbbc664d9a"}
